[1] Prolonged shedding of SARS-CoV-2 from the oral cavity?
Date: Tue 24 Nov 2020
Source: Medical Hypothesis [edited]
https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0306987720333107


ref: Troeltzsch M, Berndt R, Troeltzsch M. Is the oral cavity a reservoir for prolonged SARS-CoV-2 shedding? Medical Hypotheses. 2020; 110419; ISSN 0306-9877
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Limited knowledge about the contagiosity and case fatality rate of COVID-19 as well as the still enigmatic route of transmission have led to strict limitations of non-emergency health care especially in head and neck medicine and dentistry. There are theories that the oral cavity provides a favorable environment for SARS-CoV-2 entry and persistence which may be a risk for prolonged virus shedding. However, intraoral innate immune mechanisms provide antiviral effects against a myriad of pathogenic viruses. Initial hints of their efficacy against SARS-CoV-2 are surfacing. It is hypothesized that intraoral immune system activity modulates the invasion pattern of SARS-CoV-2 into oral cells. Thus, the significance of intraoral tissues for SARS-CoV-2 transmission and persistence cannot be assessed.

The underlying concept for this hypothesis was developed by the critical observation of a clinically asymptomatic COVID-19 patient. Despite a positive throat swab for SARS-CoV-2, molecular pathologic analysis of an oral perisulcular tissue specimen failed to detect SARS-CoV-2 RNA. More research effort is necessary to define the true origin of the contagiosity of asymptomatic COVID-19 patients.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the authors of the study above, the actual duration of shedding for potentially infectious SARS-CoV-2 particles from the upper respiratory tract and the oral cavity by acutely or formerly infected patients is still not clear and appears to be variable [1]. There is also reported data that suggest that oral epithelial cells may be extremely prone to SARS-Cov-2 infection as they have a high percentage of angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2) and transmembrane protease serine 2 (TMPRSS2) receptors that have been shown to facilitate the cellular entry of SARS-CoV-2 [2]. Additionally, the environment in the oral cavity with the periodontal pockets and the gingival tissue may be favorable for virus replication and maintenance [3]. One may theorize that these synergistic effects could potentially promote early and prolonged SARS-CoV-2 colonization of the oral cavity.

On the other hand, the oral mucosa produces high levels of defensins [4], cathelicidins and other antiviral agents which have been shown to be protective against SARS-CoV-2. The authors have hypothesized that, since a variety of immunologic mechanisms ensure a powerful barrier function of the oral cavity against invading pathogens, the importance of oral tissues for SARS-CoV-2 transmission and prolonged shedding cannot be predicted. A case report is presented of a clinically symptomatic SARS CoV2 positive case who underwent a dental extraction procedure and oral epithelial cells and underlying connective tissue were free of detectable SARS-CoV-2 RNA despite a positive throat swab, as evidence by molecular testing. This data supported the protective role of oral environment to prevent local cell invasion by the SARS-CoV-2 virus.

The authors conclude, "This knowledge would be vital to estimate at what time formerly SARS-CoV-2 positive infected patients can return to dental and head and neck physicians' offices safely to get vital but non-emergency treatment." -Mod.UBA]

References
----------
1. Li TZ, Cao ZH, Chen Y, et al. Duration of SARS-CoV-2 RNA shedding and factors associated with prolonged viral shedding in patients with COVID-19. J Med Virol. 2020:10.1002/jmv.26280. doi: 10.1002/jmv.26280. Epub ahead of print. PMID: 32644223; PMCID: PMC7362127; https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/jmv.26280.
2. Descamps G, Verset L, Trelcat A, et al. ACE2 protein landscape in the head and neck region: The conundrum of SARS-CoV-2 infection. Biology (Basel). 2020; 9(8): 235. doi: 10.3390/biology9080235. PMID: 32824830; PMCID: PMC7465650; https://www.mdpi.com/2079-7737/9/8/235/htm.
3. Kheur S, Kheur M, Gupta AA, Raj AT. Is the gingival sulcus a potential niche for SARS-Coronavirus-2? Med Hypotheses. 2020; 143: 109892. doi: 10.1016/j.mehy.2020.109892. Epub 2020 May 27. PMID: 32498008; PMCID: PMC7255245; https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0306987720311464?via%3Dihub.
4. Wang C, Wang S, Li D, et al. Human intestinal defensin 5 inhibits SARS-CoV-2 invasion by cloaking ACE2. Gastroenterology. 2020; 159(3): 1145-1147.e4. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2020.05.015. Epub 2020 May 11. PMID: 32437749; PMCID: PMC7211585; https://www.gastrojournal.org/article/S0016-5085(20)30607-7/fulltext.

