Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 218 (Samoa has not been added as yet).

Data by country, area, or territory for 26 Nov 2020 can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/WHO%20daily%20tablesNov26_1606436536.pdf.

- The Americas region reported 41.0% of daily case numbers and 37.4% of the daily deaths reported in the past 24 hours, and maintained its position as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 25.4 million cases. The USA continues to dominate, followed by Brazil, Mexico, Colombia, Argentina, and Canada. Other countries reporting more than 1000 cases include Peru, Panama, and Chile. And countries/territories reporting more than 500 cases but fewer than 1000 in the past 24 hours include Costa Rica, Paraguay, Ecuador, Guatemala, and Dominican Republic.

- The European region reported 40.6% of daily case numbers and 46.7% of the daily deaths reported in the past 24 hours, and total cumulative cases reported exceed 17.7 million. Countries not reporting cases today (25 Nov 2020) include Israel, Sweden, and Kazakhstan, among others. Countries reporting more than 10 000 cases in the past 24 hours include Italy, Russia, Germany, UK, France, Poland, and Ukraine. There are 23 additional countries reporting more than 1000 cases in the past 24 hours.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 6.5% of daily case numbers and 7.4% of the deaths reported in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 3.93 million cases. Iran is dominant, with continuing record-breaking highs, followed by Jordan, Morocco, Pakistan, Iraq, Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, UAE, and Tunisia. Libya reported more than 500 cases but fewer than 1000, while Oman, Somalia, and Yemen have not reported any cases in the past 24 hours.

- The African region reported 1.3% of daily case numbers and 1.5% of the deaths reported in the past 24 hours and has reported more than 1.47 million cases. South Africa maintains its dominance, followed by Algeria, Kenya, Ethiopia, Uganda, Nigeria, Mali, Reunion, Cabo Verde, Zimbabwe, and Cameroon.

- The Western Pacific region reported 0.88% of daily case numbers and 0.52% of the deaths reported in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of 0.85 million cases. Japan is dominant, followed by Philippines, Japan, Malaysia, South Korea, French Polynesia, China Guam, Mongolia, and Papua New Guinea. South Korea almost doubled its daily case count approaching 600 cases with all provinces reporting locally acquired infection (http://ncov.mohw.go.kr/en/bdBoardList.do?brdId=16&brdGubun=162&dataGubun&ncvContSeq&contSeq&board_id&gubun) Press release 643 at http://www.kdca.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030 has a table listing all of the clusters that did not observe social distancing.

- The South East Asia region reported 9.7% of the daily newly reported cases and 6.5% of reported deaths in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 10.5 million cases. As previously, India remains dominant, followed by Indonesia, Bangladesh, Nepal, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, and the Maldives.

Impression: Basically unchanged on the regional levels with the continued dominance of Europe and the Americas region representing over 80% of both newly confirmed cases and newly reported deaths in the past 24 hours. The USA maintains its position as the country reporting the most cases on a daily basis as transmission continues uncontrolled, expected to increase following the Thanksgiving holiday weekend (26 Nov 2020 is Thanksgiving Day).

On the Overview tab at the WHO source URL, the epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 26 Nov 2020, is an excellent visual representation of the pandemic. - Mod.MPP]

